b'' b'(ross anderson) writes:' b" wouldn't a a second monitor of similar type scrolling gibberish and adjacent" b' to the one being used provide reasonable resistance to tempest attacks?' b"we've got a tempest receiver in the lab here, and there's no difficulty in" b'picking up individual monitors. their engineering tolerances are slack enough' b'that they tend to radiate on different frequencies. even where they overlap, you' b'can discriminate because they have different line synch frequencies you can' b'lock in on one and average the others out.' b'' b'the signals are weird in any case, with varying polarisations and all sorts' b'of interactions with the building. just moving a folded dipole around is also' b'highly effective as a (randomised) means of switching from one monitor to' b'another,' b'' b'hell, just set up a spark jammer, or some other _very_ electrically-noisy' b'device. or build an active farrady cage around the room, with a "noise"' b'signal piped into it. while these measures will not totally mask the' b'emissions of your equipment, they will provide sufficient interference to' b'make remote monitoring a chancy proposition, at best. there is, of course,' b'the consideration that these measures may (and almost cretainly will)' b"cause a certain amount of interference in your own systems. it's a matter" b'of balancing security versus convenience.' b'' b"btw, i'm an ex-air force telecommunications systems control supervisor and" b'telecommunications/cryptographic equipment technician.' b'' b'--' b'remember waco!' b'who will the government decide to murder next? maybe you?' b"[opinions are mine; i don't care if you blame the university or the state.]" 